<hl>
<seg id=1> Chinese Uses World Bank Funds To Build Railroad Network </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> XINHUA NEWS AGENCY WIRE Beijing, March 17 (Qian Tong reporting): China's  Ministry of Railways will use funds from the World Bank to build a railway network linking the whole country together. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> After an extremely competitive bidding process, China Instrimpex International Tendering Company will join China United Electrical Import-Export Corporation in  providing programmed switching equipment of 220 thousand circuits in total for the Railways Ministry. The contract value will be close to 20 million U.S. dollars. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> A person from the Ministry of Railways said that this is part of a communications reconstruction project for the railway hub serving the whole country. </seg>
<seg id=5> Benefits of the project, once it is in use, will include adding Hong Kong and Macau into the network so that passengers and cargo owners can inquire about trains, reserving passenger tickets and freight space, and tracking freight movements and arrivals. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> In the last few years China has begun using funds from international financial organizations to conduct international, competitive calls for tenders for infrastructure projects. </seg>
<seg id=7> Tenders were conducted in accordance with international practice. The programmed switching mechanism produced by Shanghai Bell, represented by China United Electrical Import-Export Corporation, won the bid. </seg>
<seg id=8> It was an important order for a domestic Chinese producer of such equipment. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> According to reports, both parties to the contract were at the Diaoyutai Hotel in Beijing for the signing ceremony. </seg>
<seg id=10> Production and installation will be completed within the year. </seg>
</p>
